            <scopecontent id="aspace_b71374d756877c690925ad899f313887">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>The Selden Family Papers consists of correspondence, writings (including school essays and exercises, poetry, and political essays), and miscellaneous accounts, school bills, and other papers of the Selden family of Hadlyme, Connecticut. The papers relate principally however, to Richard Ely Selden, 1797-1868, who was a graduate of Yale University, class of 1818, a justice of the peace, and, in 1844, a member of the Connecticut state senate.</p>
               <p>The correspondence, 1795-1862, consists primarily of letters to Richard Ely Selden, a significant number being from fellow members of the class of 1818; there are also some letters form family members. Also included in the correspondence are drafts of letters that Selden wrote to others, some of these being letters to the editors of local newspapers regarding topics of political or religious interest.</p>
               <p>Among the writings are school essays and exercises, written by Richard Ely Selden and by his son, Samuel Hart Selden (Yale, 1848), with several "epic poems" by the former on political subjects.</p>
            </scopecontent>
